{[%evp 0,89,28,33,40,-14,29,37,62,51,51,51,51,51,51,51,51,26,50,48,80,76,73,64,
82,79,82,64,52,59,59,78,78,64,79,82,82,95,86,98,89,91,114,112,112,130,78,334,
327,371,359,402,404,411,471,367,367,379,392,392,390,390,390,482,527,536,560,
560,579,579,630,709,709,544,700,546,543,543,588,543,543,469,477,511,662,515,
614,614,584,561,574,602]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3
6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 {In this position, it is well-known that Black should play
c7-c5! as quickly as possible in order to fight for the center and prevent
White from simply castling. Let us take a look at the historical developments
in this line and understand how people arrived at this exact move order and
why it's not good to go 7...O-O instead} O-O $6 {This was established as a bad
move after White realized he can now simply play} 8. Be2 $1 c5 (8... b6 {
I would also like to say a few words about this move, which is the second most
popular choice in this position. White can get an advantage in many ways, but
most of all I like the ambitious} 9. h4 $1 h5 $1 $146 {The advantage of
including h2-h4 and h7-h5 is that now the g5-square is weakened. The same can
be said about the g4-square, but Black just claimed his intention to develop
the bishop on b7, not on g4, didn't he?} (9... Bb7 $6 10. e5 $1 {Now White
will definitely play h4-h5. Later, he can choose between the aggressive Be3/g5,
Qd2, hxg6, etc, or the positional h5-h6!?, switching Black's bishop off
forever, forcing it to stay on the horrible h8-square.} h5 $6 {Now it's too
late, as White has too many attacking continuations because of the Black
light-squared bishop is not controlling the c8-h3 diagonal anymore.} 11. e6 $1
$16 (11. Ng5 $5 $16)) 10. Bg5 Bb7 11. Qc2 c5 12. d5 $16 {We will continue with
Rd1, c3-c4, O-O, Rfe1, maybe Qd2-Bh6. This is an extremely enjoyable position
for White.}) 9. O-O $1 {And White is in time to deal with such moves as Bg4,
Qa5, etc. For example} Bg4 (9... Nc6 10. Be3 {And now Bg4 would transpose to
Bg4 on move 9, while the other possibility is} cxd4 11. cxd4 Bg4 {But then the
strong reply, which is exactly the reason why the line is bad for Black, is}
12. d5 $1 Ne5 (12... Bxa1 13. Qxa1 Na5 14. Bh6 f6 15. Bxf8 Qxf8 16. Nd4 Bxe2
17. Nxe2 $36 {The position would have been okay for Black with the pawn on f7,
but the pawn on f6 gives us a strong idea Nd4-Ne6!, which would absolutely
paralyze Black. Of course, we are not winning by force here, but this is a
very unpleasant position for the second player to defend.}) 13. Nxe5 Bxe2 14.
Qxe2 Bxe5 15. Rab1 $36 {Is a clear advantage for White as he has more space
and plays on the queenside}) 10. Be3 Nc6 11. d5 $1 {Is the key difference
between this position and the same position without castlings for both sides.
If Black started with 7..c5 and White tried the same way of development, here
Bxc3! with a check would be very annoying. However, here this move wouldn't be
a check anymore so White stabilizes his center and keeps a clear advantage.}
Ne5 12. Nxe5 (12. Bxc5 {Also deserves attention for White, even though after}
Rc8 13. Bd4 (13. Bxa7 $5 {Is also possible with a messy position after} Bxf3
14. Bxf3 b6 15. Rb1 Nd7 {But I would simply prefer the very main line for
White as it's much easier to handle.}) 13... Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Bxd4
16. cxd4 {Black gets some activity in return for the sacrificed pawn} Rc4 $5
$14) (12. Nd2 $5 $146 {Keeping more pieces also deserves attention.}) 12...
Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Bxe5 14. Rac1 b6 15. f4 Bg7 16. c4 $16 {Black is squeezed and
can barely do anything. White plans e4-e5!, completely burying the black
g7-bishop} *

