{[%evp 0,89,28,33,40,-14,29,37,62,51,51,51,51,51,51,51,51,26,50,48,80,76,73,64,
82,79,82,64,52,59,59,78,78,64,79,82,82,95,86,98,89,91,114,112,112,130,78,334,
327,371,359,402,404,411,471,367,367,379,392,392,390,390,390,482,527,536,560,
560,579,579,630,709,709,544,700,546,543,543,588,543,543,469,477,511,662,515,
614,614,584,561,574,602]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3
6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ $1 {The key move of our repertoire against the
Grunfeld Defense. Now, Black seemingly has a large choice. However, as you
start analyzing, you understand that two of the three moves as clearly
inferior. The reason is that the whole idea behind Grunfeld is active play and
pressure on the White center. That is why playing Bd7 or Nd7, developing
pieces to a passive square instead of the active dream-approach Nc6-Bg4!
cannot be good. On the other hand, the position remains complicated so we need
to understand a few subtleties pretty well to gain the advantage. I would also
like to mention that most players, especially ones who are not prepared for
this specific line, might be rather afraid to put the knight on c6 as they
always need to calculate the consequences of d4-d5. In fact, the move Bd7 has
even been more popular, according to the database! That is why it is so
important to study the arising positions carefully.} (8. Be2 {Let us try to
understand why this recipe, which works so well against 7..O-O, is not a
possibility here.} Nc6 $1 9. Be3 Bg4 $1 {Puts immediate pressure on the White
center. Unfortunately, this extra tempo that Black saved on castling is very
important and White cannot keep his center anymore, as} 10. e5 cxd4 11. cxd4
Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Nxd2 {Creates a position where Black has a great
control over the central d5-square and a pawn majority on the queenside. In
practice, he mostly took on e2, but such a move as Be6! seems even better.
Anyway, we don't want to go here.}) 8... Bd7 9. Be2 $1 {As we know now, White
just wants to castle and stabilize the position. That would be enough to claim
a stable advantage.} Bg4 10. Rb1 $1 {This is the main reason why the line with
Bd7 is not considered good. As we had seen before, Bxc3+ is a problem in many
lines so White removes the rook from the long diagonal while also putting
pressure on b7. Black can choose to either play calmly and finish the
development or choose a rather forcing approach which leads him to a somewhat
worse simplified position.} O-O (10... cxd4 {Would transpose to 10...O-O} 11.
cxd4 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Bxd4 13. Rxb7 O-O 14. O-O Nc6) 11. O-O cxd4 12. cxd4 {
Now something like ...b6 or ...Nc6 would give White a type of advantage we are
already familiar with, while the forcing move is} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Bxd4 {This is
the move we need to consider carefully as the great Grunfeld expert Ian
Nepomniachtchi used it to draw Andreikin. However, he was fighting for
equality during the entire game, and the position was still remaining
unpleasant. If Andreikin could pose problems to a 2750+ player, hopefully, our
opponents wouldn't find their life easy either.} (13... Qxd4 14. Be3 $5 {
Almost a novelty - this happened only in two games by players around 2100.
White is sure he would get his pawn back and asks Black to trade and improve
the position of the f1-rook} Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Nc6 16. Rxb7 {The White bishops
are raging, Black's position is very bad here. Rc7, Rd7, e4-e5 are all threats,
the pawn on a7 is also very weak.}) 14. Rxb7 Nc6 15. Qa4 $1 (15. Bh6 Bg7 16.
Qxd8 Nxd8 17. Bxg7 Nxb7 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 19. Rc1 {Might be a slight advantage too,
but looks drawish.}) 15... Qc8 (15... Qd6 {Is the most popular move, but White
keeps an advantage thanks to his bishops and the active rooks. For example,}
16. Rb5 Rfd8 17. Rd5 Qe6 18. Rd1 Bb6 19. Bb2 $16 {And White went on to win an
impressive game in Yakovich-Danielian, Kavala 2009}) 16. Rb3 Qe6 17. h3 $5 $146
{prevents Rc8 as Bg4! would be a problem and creates a threat of e4-e5! After}
(17. e5 $5 {Is another interesting move, which is the main line. But I think
the game becomes too drawish here.} Rac8 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 19. Qxd4 Qxc1 20. e6 $1
(20. Qxa7 Qc5 $1 21. Qxc5 Rxc5 22. f4 Ra8 23. a3 Rc2 {And Black is too active
to risk to lose here.}) 20... Qc5 (20... fxe6 21. Qxa7 Qc5 $14 {Would allow
White to put pressure on Black for a while - either with queens, as the Black
king is weaker, on without. I would rather prefer to keep the queens and try
to pursue the plan h4-h5, eventually opening the Black king even more.}) 21.
exf7+ Rxf7 {Andreikin reached this position twice versus Nepo and tried two
moves - Qd1 and Qd2. This is not a forcing position and the concrete moves
don't matter too much - Black is close to equality, but White keeps some
advantage - there would not be many players willing to go here as White, and
17.h3! keeps even more tension on the board, so we have nothing to worry about
here.}) 17... Rad8 18. Bg4 Qf6 19. Bh6 $14 {Any grandmaster would pick White
here, as his pieces are more active and he has a long term asset - a pair of
bishops.} *

