1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Bb5+ Bd7 9. Be2 cxd4 $5 {This capture wouldn't be a good idea at all, if it
wasn't connected with Black's next move, which is rather concrete. However, I
would like you to understand that in general Black doesn't want to take on d4
early, as he loses the flexibility and the possibilities to capture on d4
later, at a moment of his choosing. Normally, this move is either not good
strategically or it is justified by some concrete variation/idea.} (9... O-O
10. O-O cxd4 (10... Nc6 11. Rb1 $1 $16 {This looks very similar and White
enjoys the same type of advantage. Now d4-d5 and c3-c4 are coming.}) 11. cxd4
Nc6 12. Rb1 $1 {Again, we see the same idea in action: the rook leaves the
a1-h8 diagonal as soon as possible.} b6 13. d5 (13. h3 $5 {It's also possible
to keep the pawn on d4 for now while making a useful move, stopping ...Bg4 for
good.}) 13... Na5 14. h3 $16 e6 15. Bg5 Bf6 16. Bh6 Bg7 17. Bg5 Bf6 18. Bh6 Bg7
19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qd4+ (20. d6 $1 $146 {And Black would have had a rather hard
time dealing with the passed pawn on d6, which is about to be supported by
e4-e5!}) 20... Kg8 $2 (20... f6 $1 {This would have at least prepared ...e6-e5,
where Black could resist longer.}) 21. d6 $16 {White was nearly winning and
went on to win a lovely game 1-0 (34) Almasi,I (2400)-Bajusz,G (2240) Gyula
1993}) (9... Nc6 10. O-O cxd4 11. cxd4 {1-0 (34) Almasi,I (2400)-Bajusz,G 
(2240) Gyula 1993}) 10. cxd4 Bc6 $1 {If our rook wasn't on a1, we could simply
play d4-d5, kicking this bishop out with a tempo. Unfortunately, this is not
the case so we need to make a slightly clumsy move. However, it's not really a
big deal as our goal here is not to win as many tempi as possible. Instead,
our task is to stabilize the position and keep the advantage thanks to our
lovely center.} (10... Nc6 11. Rb1 $1 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qxa2 13. Rxb7 {Now the
d7-bishop is under attack so Black cannot castle, while after} Rb8 (13... Nxd4
$2 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. O-O $18 {Black did win the pawn, but now he cannot castle
as the d7-bishop is hanging. Even more importantly, now the White queen is
eyeing down both bishops over the d-file, this was the price Black had to pay
for that d4-pawn. I don't think there's a satisfactory defense to ideas like
Bh6, Rxd7, etc.}) 14. Rxb8+ Nxb8 15. O-O O-O 16. Qb1 $1 $14 {White gets a
large advantage thanks to his extra pawn in the center. In this position, he
scored the lovely 2.5/3, which also does say something.}) 11. Qd3 $1 O-O (11...
f5 $6 {This was tried by numerous good players, but in the pre-computer era.
The brutal engines immediately prove that it's not a good idea to weaken the
king so significantly, especially while it's still in the center on e8.} 12.
Qb3 $1 (12. e5 $5 {Also keeps a nice edge as the g7-bishop is now rather
useless.}) 12... Qb6 $1 (12... Bxe4 $2 $146 13. Ng5 $1 Bd5 14. Bc4 $18 {
And Black's position is falling apart.}) 13. Qc4 $1 Na6 (13... Bxe4 $2 14. Ng5
$16) 14. O-O Qb4 15. exf5 Qxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Bxd4 18. Rb1 Nc5 19. Re1
{This is how all the games continued, but White has a large advantage here!
For example,} Bf6 20. Be3 b6 21. a4 $1 gxf5 22. a5 $1 {The White bishops are
simply too strong and soon this activity yielded him a nice win in the
following correspondence game.} Bc3 23. axb6 axb6 24. Red1 Ba5 25. Bd4 Rf8 26.
Bg7 e6 27. Bxf8 Kxf8 28. Rd6 Ke7 29. Rc6 Kf6 30. Ra1 Ke7 31. Rc7+ {1-0 (31)
Piscopia,C (2015)-Colucci,M ICCF email 2013}) (11... Nd7 12. Rb1 $1 {White
removes the rook away from the x-ray over the a1-h8 diagonal and prepares
d4-d5.} O-O 13. O-O (13. d5 $146 {To my huge surprise, this natural move is a
novelty! White, however, is undoubtedly more comfortable here, for example}
Qa5+ 14. Nd2 Ba4 15. O-O $16 {The White knight is coming to b3 or c4. It's
difficult to explain what the Black bishop is doing on a4, on the other hand.})
13... Rc8 14. Be3 a6 15. d5 Bb5 16. Qd1 Bxe2 17. Qxe2 b5 18. Rfc1 $14 {White
reached a very pleasant edge in this game, too, even though eventually the
opponents ended up splitting the point. 1/2 (71) Dragnev,V (2461)-Ragger,M 
(2644) Austria 2018}) 12. O-O e6 13. Bg5 Qa5 14. Rfc1 $16 {White's advantage
is rather obvious here. Later, we can consider Qe3 followed by h4-h5, which is
especially justified as the Black pieces are far away from the kingside.} *

