1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Bb5+ Bd7 9. Be2 Qa5 $5 {This is a rather rare move, however it is the one that
is getting rather trendy, as lately it has been used by Svidler and Shankland
among others. On top of that, it was recently recommended by Delchev in his
book on Grunfeld, published in 2019, so we need to study this continuation
rather carefully. Black is immedaitely putting pressure on the c3-pawn, making
us defend it.} 10. Bd2 {White has to make this clumsy-looking move, but this
is not a huge achievement for the opponent, whose very own pieces - the bishop
on d7 and the queen on a5 - are not necessarily placed too well.} (10. O-O {
It is always interesting to check the pawn sacrifice, but after} Qxc3 11. Bd2
Qa3 12. Rb1 O-O $1 $13 {Black castles and avoids any problems, in my opinion.})
10... O-O (10... Qa4 {Transposes} 11. O-O O-O {And we are back in the main
line.}) 11. O-O Qa4 12. Be3 $5 $146 {This is a novelty. Delchev analyses Rb1
and Bg5 in this move, but I like this natural move better - we are firmly
protecting our center!} (12. Rb1 {This is also a fairly interesting
continuation, however, Black has several reasonable possibilities - both ...
Qxa2 and ...b7-b6 look rather reliable to me.} b6 13. Bg5 Qxd1 14. Rfxd1 Ba4
15. Rdc1 e6 $132 {I believe that Black is rather comfortable here - pay
specific attention to the excellent position of his a4-bishop, which is
controlling the crucial d1-square while also allowing Black to develop his
knight conveniently. We might be a little better here, but Black's play will
be too easy here.}) 12... Qxd1 (12... b6 13. Qd2 $14 {White stabilizes his
position and should have an edge thanks to his powerful center. After we play
Rfc1! in a move or two, Black might actually get rather worried about the
c5-pawn, while releasing the tension with ...cxd4 is clearly not too
favourable for him. Another idea worth mentioning is h2-h3!, taking the
g4-square under control and stopping ...Bg4. The bishop is not placed well on
d7, as it is preventing Black for pressuring our center over the d-file while
also taking the d7-square away from the knight.}) 13. Raxd1 {Now we reach a
rather comfortable endgame. This very position is brand-new, however such type
of endgames is rather standard, so it's instructive to follow White's upcoming
play. How to improve our position from now on?} e6 {Black is immediately
restraining our potential ideas related with d4-d5.} (13... Ba4 $5 {It's
interesting what happens if Black tries to occupy this lovely square on a4,
while also preventing us from controlling the d-file.} 14. Rb1 {White
immediately finds other targets.} b6 15. Rfc1 {White has protected the c3-pawn,
now the positional threat is d4-d5! followed by c3-c4. Black totally has to
stop this idea.} e6 (15... Nd7 16. Nd2 $1 {The same idea as the one that we
see after 15...e6 again proves very useful.} Rac8 17. Ba6 Rc7 18. d5 {White
has firmly seized the initiative, he is ready to play Bf4, Nc4, possibly e4-e5!
} Ne5 19. Nc4 {White would benefit a lot from the knight trade as Black would
have a lot less counterplay against our center.} Nxc4 20. Bxc4 Rd7 {It looks
as though Black gets a pretty solid position, which is partially true - it's
not easy to break through. However, the game is rather one-sided here, and a
good way for White to improve his position would be} 21. f4 $1 Re8 22. g4 $14 {
We keep grabbing space, while Black has to helplessly watch our position
improve. These is definitely no need to shy away from such scenario.}) 16. Nd2
$1 {This is a very important and remarkable maneuvre. The knight had nothing
to do on f3, so we are transferring it to c4. Now the e4-pawn can be protected
additionally with f2-f3, while in some cases f2-f4 might be an idea worth
going for, provided our center is stable, as this move will gain us even more
space.} Nd7 (16... Rc8 17. dxc5 Nd7 (17... bxc5 18. Bb5 $1 Bxb5 19. Rxb5 $16 {
With incredibly strong pressure on the queenside. Please note how useless and
passive all the Black pieces are!}) 18. cxb6 axb6 19. Nc4 Bc6 20. Rb2 $16) 17.
Nc4 $14 {White simply keeps improving his position - now f2-f3 and Kf2 are the
next obvious moves.} Rac8 $6 18. Nd6 {White can consider either making an
outpost out of the d6-square by means of e4-e5, which will also shut down the
g7-bishop, or he can try some tricks related to Nb5-a7 in some variations.
Either way, our position is incredibly enjoyable, so it was possible to cut
the analysis short earlier, but I am trying to provide you with a deeper
middlegame understanding.}) (13... cxd4 {I believe that it's not a good idea
to release the tension early, as after} 14. cxd4 e6 {White quickly gets a
powerful passed pawn in the center. Please note that the Black queenside
pieces are not ready to participate in the game at all.} 15. d5 $1 exd5 16.
exd5 $16) 14. d5 (14. Ne5 $5 {This is another fairly promising continuation,
as the knight is coming to c4, just as in other variations above.} Ba4 15. Rd2
$5 {This might appear to be an ugly move, but White is protecting the d4-pawn
which proves instrumental in the line seen after 13.Rb1.} (15. Rb1 Nc6 16. Nd7
cxd4 17. cxd4 Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Rd7,Re2][%cal Gd4e2,Ga4d7] And everything works
out just fine for Black from the tactical perspective, as the e2-bishop, as
well as the d7-knight, are hanging.}) 15... Nd7 (15... Rc8 16. Nc4) 16. Nc4 {
The position is by no means forcing, so let us analyze a sample continuation}
Rfc8 17. Rb1 cxd4 18. cxd4 {The engine is rather confident that Black is doing
okay, but I believe the second player should be extremely careful as the
d-pawn might run down the board really fast!} Nf6 $6 (18... Bf8 $1 $11 19. d5
exd5 20. exd5 b6 21. d6 Bc6 22. Bf4 $13 {Again, White is clearly pressing - at
least, from the practical perspective!}) 19. f3 $16) 14... exd5 15. exd5 b6 (
15... Bxc3 {Obviously, taking the pawn is rather principled. However, White
immediately gets the sacrificed material back.} 16. Rc1 Bb4 (16... Bg7 17. Bxc5
{I am afraid the g7-bishop is going to be somewhat out of play here.} Rc8 18.
Be3 Na6 (18... Bg4 $2 {Black wants to free up the d7-square for the knight,
but it does not work out well after} 19. Nd4 $1 Bd7 20. Rxc8+ Bxc8 21. Nb5 {
Just look at the Black pieces - I am under an impression that he is getting
ready for the next game!} Na6 22. Nxa7 $16 {Thiis is just a free pawn, White
should have a technically winning position now.}) 19. d6 $36 Nb4 20. Bc4 $36 {
Again, Black's life is rather tough.}) 17. Bxc5 Bxc5 18. Rxc5 Re8 {Black's
development is still rather problematic after any sensible move, such as Bd3/
Bc4/Nd4.} 19. Bc4 $36) 16. c4 Re8 (16... Ba4 17. Rc1 Nd7 18. Bd1 $5 {The
bishop on a4 is rather annoying, so it's well worth trading it.} Bxd1 19. Rfxd1
{White has a very comfortable one-sided type of position where he can either
try to put pressure on the queenside by means of the typical a2-a4-a5, or gain
more space on the kingside with g2-g3, Kg2, h2-h4 etc.}) 17. Bd3 $5 {The
bishop is coming to c2 and a4.} Bg4 18. Bc2 $1 Nd7 19. Ba4 Red8 {We are
already very deep in some theoretical jungles, but it looks like White keeps
putting pressure. We will be extremely glad to trade the light-squared bishops,
as then the powerful d5-pawn, as well as ideas like a2-a4-a5, will provide us
with a very comfortable advantage.} 20. Bc6 {For instance, now such moves are
logical:} Rac8 21. Bb5 Ne5 (21... Kf8 {Let's see what happens if Black just
waits and asks us to show our hand.} 22. h3 Bxf3 23. gxf3 $16 {While will now
go Rfe1, Kg2 etc, continuing to calmly improve his position.} Bd4 24. Bxd4 (24.
Bh6+ {If we don't want to allow for the blockade, this also keeps a nice edge.}
) 24... cxd4 25. Rxd4 Nc5 {Yes, sure, Black has chances to hold, but he is
fighting hard for his life and we are risking nothing, so why not go here?})
22. Nxe5 $5 Bxd1 23. Nc6 Rxc6 24. Bxc6 Be2 25. Rc1 {This position should be
holdable, but undoubtedly White is for choice.} *

