1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8.
Bb5+ Nd7 {This is a seemingly "fighting" move which allows Black to keep more
pieces on the board while also not allowing for the forcing variations that we
are about to see in the next chapters. Sounds attractive, doesn't it?
Unfortunately, everything in chess comes at a certain cost. In this case,
Black's knight will be placed extremely passively, which will prevent him from
pursuing the main idea of Grunfeld - it will be nearly impossible for him to
put pressure on the White center!} 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 $5 {White prepares the
f1-square for his bishop.} a6 (10... Qa5 {Jumabayev tried this move and even
won the game, but it wasn't thanks to the opening choice, as after the logical}
11. a4 $1 {White stops the plan of ...a7-a6 followed by ...b7-b5 and gets a
large advantage.} a6 (11... Qxc3 $2 12. Bd2 Qb2 13. Re2 $1 {Creates a threat
of trapping the queen by means of Be1/Ba5 and pretty much wins the game.}) 12.
Bf1 Rd8 13. Qb3 e6 14. Bg5 Re8 {Up to this point White played well, and what
he did in the game was fine, but it would have been even stronger to shut down
the Black g7-bishop by means of} 15. e5 $1 $16 {Black's position is truly
disastrous. One obvious idea to mention is Nd2-c4-d6, the opponent has a very
hard time stopping it. Another plan would be h2-h4-h5, followed by an attack
against the Black barely protected king.}) 11. Bf1 {Now several moves were
tried, but we wouldn't discuss stuff like ...Nb8 or ...e7-e6. The only natural,
ambitious attempt to get the counterplay is} b5 {however, it is not reasonable
to hope for counterplay by making the weakening pawn moves when the pieces are
not ready to support the pawn play.} 12. a4 $1 b4 13. cxb4 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Qb6
15. Be3 Qxb4 16. Nc6 $18 {White was already completely winning and only very
stubborn defense together with a fair amount of luck allowed Black to bail out.
1/2 (119) Steingrimsson,H (2550)-Navara,D (2722) Reykjavik 2010} *

