{[%evp 0,33,25,25,19,-15,42,45,57,57,51,51,51,45,51,51,51,40,41,29,34,7,22,30,
30,22,51,21,41,32,26,56,56,55,69,69]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5
5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. d5 $5 {The most forcing move.
It has never been considered dangerous, as people believed Black has about 3-4
decent continuations. However, while I was not able to find advantage for
White in every single line, I realized that only one(!) variation can be
called a reliable solution for him! In many lines he almost loses by force,
instead. For example, I have managed to find a new idea and pose problems for
Black in the line that Avrukh recommends in his GM Repertoire book on Grunfeld.
I have consulted other sources too - GM Delchev in his first book "Safest
Grunfeld" doesn't consider 9.d5 at all, while GM Milos Pavlovic in his work
"Unknown Weapons in the Grunfeld" doesn't analyze 8.Bb5 whatsoever.} a6 {
Just as Qa5, this is one of the two only moves in this position. But even
though MVL had used it in 2008, to me it looks extremely dangerous.} 10. Be2
Bxc3+ {The main move by far. But the arising position looks extremely
dangerous to me.} (10... Ne5 {Is another possibility, and it looks extremely
similar to the variation in 8.Rb1, where Black plays Nc6-Ne5 and his bishop
eventually retreats to c7. But here we can save some time on Rb1!} 11. Nxe5
Bxe5 12. Qd2 $146 {Just playing in the same way, but trying to prove that our
extra tempo is worth something. Which, of course, should be the case, as the
position is rather complicated and sharp.} e6 13. f4 Bc7 14. Ba3 $5 exd5 15.
exd5 Qe7 16. O-O O-O 17. c4 {Then White will play Rae1, Bb2, Qc3. I believe
that it would be easier to play as White, to say the least. And quite likely,
objectively he is also just better.}) 11. Bd2 {Now we need to play an exchange
down, but we have a very strong long-term initiative for it.} Bxa1 12. Qxa1 Nd4
13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 f6 (14... O-O {This is what Avrukh recommends in his
book on Grunfeld} 15. h4 {However, he analyses only 15.Bh6 or castling,
failing to consider h4. Now 15..f6 16.O-O would transpose to the previous note,
which is something we are more than happy with. So let's look at some other
attempts by Black besides f6} Bd7 $5 (15... h5 {Now Bh6 would be rather strong,
or you can castle and play our standard position} 16. O-O $1 {This variation
is not for greedy players who attempt to get their exchange back. Make
yourself comfortable, enjoy your compensation!} (16. Bh6 Qa5+ 17. Kf1 f6 18.
Bxf8 Kxf8 {With the pawns on h4 and h5 it's better for White. However, Black
eventually equalizes here.}) 16... f6 17. Qe3 {And we are back to our analysis
of 13..f6}) 16. h5 {White pursues his very straightforward plan} Rc8 17. hxg6
fxg6 18. O-O $16 {The long diagonal is incredibly weak right now, so Black is
in a lot of long-term trouble. We are ready to just play Bc3. This is not a
convincing solution for Black at all.}) 15. h4 O-O (15... h5 {Main move
according to the database. However, only 5 games were played here and players
were under 2200, so it's not too relevant for the state of theory} 16. O-O {
Now, it's surprisingly difficult for Black to find a move. Two games saw
castling here, in two other ones b7-b5 was played, and in the other one the
best, in my opinion, move - Bg4 was essayed.} O-O {Is a very dangerous move
because of the following instructive maneuvre} (16... Bg4 $1 {Intending to
trade the dangerous bishop and delaying castling} 17. Bc4 $5 $146 (17. Bd3 $5 {
Is also interesting and deserves further investigation. This was played in the
only game that had reached this position}) 17... Qd6 18. Qe3 Rc8 19. Bb3 Kf7 {
White keeps a great compensation, even though it looks like Black seems to be
defending so far. However, I would still like to go in some detail here, as
Black's position seems to be very scary. We would like to play Bc3 and e5, but
Black has a strong defense Qc5! attacking the bishop and trading queens.
However, our bishop still belongs to the long diagonal! So we can play. ..Bc1,
Qd2, Bb2! Our compensation is very long-term, you would never get worse here
as White.} 20. Bc1 $1 {Black can try to block the position with e7-e5 or stay
passive. Let's see how we pose problems if Black does nothing - for example,
if we go Re8, Rd8 or that sort of moves.} Rhe8 21. e5 $1 Qxe5 (21... fxe5 22.
Bb2 $1 {Finally the route for the bishop has been cleared up! This may sound
like an exaggeration, but according to AlphaZero, White is already winning.}
Red8 23. Bxe5 Qc5 24. d6+ e6 25. Qf4+ Ke8 26. Qf6 $18) 22. d6+ Kg7 (22... Be6
23. d7 $18) 23. Qh6# {Checkmate!}) 17. Qe3 $1 {Now White executes the
following idea. The queen is obviously coming to h6 and the light-squared
bishop can go to c4 or to d1 and b3! On that diagonal, it's very dangerous.
And we are back to our analysis of 13..f6} Rf7 18. Bc4 Bd7 19. Qg3 Kh7 20. d6
e6 21. e5 $1 f5 (21... fxe5 22. Bd3 Qf6 23. Bc3 {Black is tied up and down and
White is simply crushing him. This is already resignable.})) 16. h5 g5 17. h6
Bd7 18. Rh5 $1 {[%cal Gh5g5] Key idea} Bb5 (18... Kh8 19. Rxg5 e5 20. dxe6 Bxe6
21. Qb2 {White wants to just go Bc3. He has a pawn for the exchange and a very
strong dark-squared bishop, while the Black king's position is extremely
fragile. White's big advantage is undisputable here}) 19. Rxg5+ Kh8 20. Bg4 $16
*

