{[%evp 0,55,16,25,29,-16,34,43,83,83,77,66,66,69,52,52,46,23,23,51,27,16,28,28,
28,28,10,16,28,-27,8,-64,-19,-9,-18,-10,-10,-10,-7,-52,-32,-31,-33,-51,-23,-64,
-26,-26,-31,-49,-99,0,0,0,75,75,75,29]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5
Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. d5 $5 Qa5 {The most
popular continuation, used by such eminent players as MVL, Grischuk, Gelfand,
Jonas, Areshchenko and many others} 10. Rb1 {Now a6 is much more popular, but
Bc3 looks rather principled, so both moves are worth checking.} a6 $2 {This
was used by many 2600+ and 2650+ GMs, but I would dare to call this move very
dangerous for Black, if not almost losing! This was a shocking discovery to me
and a very rewarding result of research.} 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. O-O Qxa2 13. Rb2
$1 (13. Bg5 $5 {This is Svidler's suggestion in his fantastic course on
Grunfeld for chess24 and this remains a novelty still, even now. However,
after 15..Qb5, as I mention, I cannot find how to pose problems to Black} cxd5
14. Ra1 Qc4 15. Ra4 Qxc3 (15... Qb5 $1 {Svidler isn't mentioning this move,
but I was unable to find anything threatening for White} 16. exd5 h6 17. c4 Qb6
18. Bf4 O-O 19. Be5) 16. Qxd5 Ra7 17. Rc4 Qa3 18. Qc6+ Bd7 19. Qb6 Ra8 20. Rd1
$1 {Now Rxd7 is a large threat and Black in walking by very thin ice} f6 21.
Rxd7 fxg5 22. Rxe7+ Kxe7 23. Qc7+ Kf8 24. Qd6+ Ke8 25. Qc6+ Ke7 26. Qb7+ Kd6
27. Qd5+ Ke7 28. Qb7+ Kd6 29. Qxg7 {This is somewhat too lengthy, but I wanted
to understand myself and demonstrate, why Black is in so much danger}) 13...
Qa5 14. d6 Ra7 {And here Anand-Gelfand from the 2012 WCH saw Bg5, but I would
like to suggest Bf4. This was tried in three games, and I think it's very
interesting.} 15. Bf4 $1 {Now in 2 games Rd7 was played and in the other one
Black castled.} Rd7 {And here in both games White played the passive Rd2.
However, of course, the much more ambitious Rb8! is the only challenging
continuation} (15... O-O 16. Ne5 $1 exd6 (16... Bxe5 $5 {The only game that
reached this position saw this move. Even though players aren't as high-rated 
( 2184 vs 2241), it's a correspondence game, so we should study it very
carefully.} 17. Bxe5 {In my opinion, White should have better chances as his
bishop is more useful. Let's see how the game develops.} Re8 18. Rb8 (18. Qf3
$5 {Also looks interesting} exd6 19. Bxd6 Rd7 20. e5 $36 {With a lot of
pressure. Black is a pawn up, but it doesn't matter, as all of his pawns are
weak and his king is quite problematic, too. I think we can stop here - White
preserves a clear positional advantage, we should be happy with such an
outcome.}) 18... Qd8 19. Bf4 exd6 20. Qxd6 Qxd6 21. Bxd6 c4 22. f3 {And
eventually Black was able to hold this position, but he had to work hard for a
draw.} a5 23. Ra1 Ra6 24. Ra4 Bd7 25. Rxe8+ Bxe8 26. Bc5 Bd7 27. Kf2 f5 28. Ke3
fxe4 29. fxe4 Kf7 30. Kd4 {1/2 (30) Andersen,J (2184)-Hryniw,M (2241) ICCF
email 2012}) 17. Nxc6 Qxc3 18. Rb3 Qf6 $8 19. Nxa7 Qxf4 20. Nxc8 Rxc8 21. Qd5
$1 {And as a result, we reach an interesting position. Black has two pawns for
the exchange, so material-wise his position must be fine. However, things are
not so simple: Rb7 would prove very annoying, and Black's a-pawn is really
weak. So we should check first, what happens if he tries to push his c-pawn} c4
$2 (21... Qe5 22. Rfb1 Qxd5 23. exd5 {Now White will trade rooks by force, and
even if it's close to some fortress, White will be pushing for long.} Be5 24.
Rb8 Rxb8 25. Rxb8+ Kg7 26. Ra8 Kf6 27. Rxa6 {Importantly, Black cannot win the
d5-pawn fast, let's see why. If that's not the case, White will just improve
his king and try to win. I don't think it's a smart idea to try to analyze
this until a forced win or draw, but I would like to point a few ideas. First,
a classical one - we can keep our rook on 7th rank and then try to bring the
king to e8 via d3-c4-b5-c6-d7-e8! Another thing we can try is g3-f4, kicking
the bishop away from e5, when the d6-pawn can become weak. Anyway, first of
all, you should not be disappointed with such an outcome of the opening - yes,
opening!, even though we are deep through the line on move 27. And secondly,
the opponent has to know everything to end up in such a sad position!} Kf5 28.
f3 Bd4+ 29. Kf1 Ke5 30. Ra7 Kf6) 22. Rf3 $1 {That's the point! The white rook
has a lot of routes, and Black loses instantly. It's a very important
variation.}) 16. Rb8 $1 $146 {Now the variation is very forcing} O-O 17. dxe7
$1 Rxe7 (17... Rxd1 18. exf8=Q+ $18) 18. Bd6 Rd7 19. Bxf8 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Bxf8
21. Rxc8 {If White had an escape square, he would have won instantly. Here
it's not as simple, but White still has a big advantage. Let's check a few
moves by Black} Qxc3 22. h4 Kg7 23. e5 $1 {As can be seen by last two moves,
White is playing for..checkmate! The black bishop has very limited mobility
and the simple Rd8 is a rather annoying threat. But besides that, another big
problem is that e5-e6! is coming.} a5 24. e6 $1 Qb3 $1 (24... fxe6 $2 {Now Rd7
looks decisive, but gives Black counterplay Fortunately, Ng5 is winning.} 25.
Ng5 (25. Rd7+ Kg8 26. Rdd8 Qc1+ 27. Kh2 Qf4+ 28. Kh3 a4 29. Rxf8+ Qxf8 30.
Rxf8+ Kxf8 {And by some miracle Black is holding this}) 25... Be7 26. Rc7 Kf8
27. Rb1 $1 {And the rook is coming to b8 with decisive effect.} a4 28. Rb8+ Kg7
29. Rxe7+ $18) 25. Re1 $1 {Threatening e7} fxe6 26. Ng5 Be7 27. Rc7 Kf6 28.
Rxc6 $18 {And White is still winning. As we can see in all of these lines, the
rooks and the knight prove significantly stronger than the Black queen and his
restricted bishop.} *

