{[%evp 0,40,29,29,18,-19,43,37,83,83,52,46,47,54,37,39,43,23,37,28,28,28,45,45,
34,-2,-7,-7,55,18,15,29,62,20,32,21,21,26,8,12,18,18,35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3.
Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. d5 $5 Qa5 {
The most popular continuation, used by such eminent players as MVL, Grischuk,
Gelfand, Jonas, Areshchenko and many others} 10. Rb1 {Now a6 is much more
popular, but Bc3 looks rather principled, so both moves are worth checking.}
Bxc3+ {The less frequent move, but it was played by MVL and Grischuk. Also,
importantly, it was recommended by the great Svidler in his course. This is
the one I had most problems with, and here it's barely possible to find a
theoretical advantage. But there are still things your opponent has to know!}
11. Bd2 a6 $1 ({After the naive} 11... Bxd2+ $2 12. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 {
Even though Black is not losing a piece, he gets a losing position after} a6 $8
14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. dxc6 Be6 16. Rb7 Rc8 17. c7 Kd7 18. Ne5+ Kd6 19. f4 $1 {
The point being that} Rxc7 $4 (19... f6 20. Rb6+ Kxc7 21. Rxe6 fxe5 22. Rxe7+
Kc6 23. Rxe5 $18 {Is winning for White - just an extra pawn and a better
position.}) 20. Rb6+ $1 {Is a checkmate. So Black cannot unpin or untangle.})
12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. dxc6 Be6 $1 (13... Bxd2+ 14. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 Be6 16. Rb7
{Is a horrible position for Black, again - we just transpose to 11..Bxd2? See
that line.}) 14. Rc1 Bxd2+ 15. Qxd2 Qb4 $1 {The key nuance which was pointed
out by Svidler. The point of this move is that Black wants us to castle, which
worsens our king's position as the endgame is approaching and we would like to
keep it in the center. What gives us hope is that even MVL didn't play this
move, so why would your opponent necessarily find it?} 16. O-O Qxd2 17. Nxd2
O-O-O $1 {The last key move. Instead, 17..Ba2? leads to problems.} (17... Bxa2
$2 18. Rxc5 O-O-O 19. Rc2 Be6 20. Rb1 $16 {With a large advantage - Rb7 is
very annoying. Also, White's king would come to the center quickly after f4,
Kf2, Ke3.}) 18. Nb3 Bxb3 19. axb3 Rd3 20. Rxc5 Rxb3 {And soon draw was
achieved from this position in the game Sasikiran-Grischuk, 2012. However,
there are reasons why I would be strongly inclined to recommend that you try 9.
d5, and keep it in your repertoire at least as a dangerous surprise weapon.
The main one is because other moves lead to very dangerous, often losing
positions for Black, and only one(!) game showed the right solution for Black.
This is definitely a very encouraging sign. And if your opponent finds 20
precise only moves, congratulations - you drew a very strong player!} *

