{[%evp 0,96,25,-14,38,38,38,43,48,39,39,43,36,41,41,46,34,31,35,-1,12,6,19,16,
5,11,11,-1,18,3,28,12,34,0,89,-16,46,-54,6,-62,9,-14,-4,-115,-25,-63,-62,-67,
-28,-66,-68,-70,-98,-105,-105,-129,-139,-121,-121,-132,-129,-153,-154,-136,
-148,-154,-124,-154,-154,-157,-127,-154,-224,-193,-112,-202,-227,-227,-243,
-236,-226,-241,-332,-219,-246,-254,-227,-227,-250,-227,-256,-255,-270,-387,
-415,-415,-415,-1360,-1307]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4
Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ (8. Rb1 Nc6 {1/2 (27) Poschke,M-Von Rahden,
A Berlin 1993}) 8... Nc6 9. Rb1 $5 {Here we go! Some of you might be unhappy
either because 9.d5 leads to an equal nearly drawn position if Black plays
perfectly, or because there is too much to learn. So, we will also analyze
this rare move introduced by Daniil Dubov, who is known for his fantastic
creative opening ideas. White just removes the rook from the a1-h8 diagonal
and prepares the move d4-d5, wanting to see how Black will react.} O-O (9...
Qa5 {Black is immediately threatening the c3-pawn. Now White has multiple ways
to get an edge, but most of all I like the simple} 10. Qa4 $1 {The cleanest
path.} Qxa4 11. Bxa4 {Now the obvious threat is d4-d5. Besides that, ideas
like Ba3 are also very annoying, and the rook is doing an excellent job on the
b-file!} O-O (11... Bd7 $2 12. Rxb7 $18) 12. Ba3 $36 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nxd4 $2 (
13... a6 14. d5 $36 {The e7-pawn is hanging and Black is already in serious
trouble.}) 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Bxe7 $18 {And the f8-rook is trapped!}) (9... Bg4
$2 10. d5 $1 {This is when we see the advantage of our 9th move, as the rook
isn't hanging!} Bxc3+ 11. Bd2 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Bxd2+ 13. Qxd2 a6 {1/2 (27)
Poschke,M-Von Rahden,A Berlin 1993} 14. Ba4 $146 {The pin forces Black to play
b5} b5 15. dxc6 Qxd2+ 16. Kxd2 O-O-O+ 17. Ke3 bxa4 18. Rb7 $16 {And Black's
position is nearly lost, as White's rooks will be extremely active on the 7th
rank, now Rxe7 and Rhb1 are the two almost decisive threats.}) (9... cxd4 10.
cxd4 {The positions here would look similar to the ones covered elsewhere in
the chapter, but the inclusion of ...cxd4 cxd4 clearly benefits White as Black
could take at a moment of his choosing, there was no need to capture right now.
}) 10. d5 Na5 11. O-O {The a5-knight isn't making Black's position too
beautiful. Now we will improve our position with moves like Qd3, Ba4, c3-c4,
Re1 etc.} b6 (11... e6 {Undermining the center is frequently a good idea, but
perhaps not here, as now White's d-pawn will be too strong.} 12. d6 $1 a6 13.
Be2 {The positional threat is e4-e5!} b5 14. e5 $36 {a2-a4! is about to come,
breaking Black's structure apart. Importantly, Black is not able to challenge
our center as after} f6 15. a4 $1 {And Black's position is collapsing, for
instance} fxe5 16. axb5 axb5 17. Rxb5 $18) (11... Bxc3 $6 12. Qc2 Bg7 13. Qxc5
$16 {White gets his pawn back and keeps a serious advantage thanks to his
impressive center.}) 12. Bf4 $5 {It's always a good idea to simply develop a
piece! White can now continue with Ne5-c6, or with Qd2, Rfe1, Rad1, e4-e5, etc.
} Bxc3 {Taking the pawn is the only critical move, or else Black will just be
under a lot of pressure for no compensation.} 13. Qc1 $1 (13. e5 {It would
have been to switch Black's c3-bishop out of play, but unfortunately Black is
getting counterplay after} Bf5 $1 14. Rc1 Bb2 $1 $132) 13... Bg7 14. Ne5 {
The White center is extremely impressive, while Black's a5-knight is out of
play and his extra pawn doesn't tell at all.} e6 (14... Bxe5 $6 15. Bxe5 f6 16.
Bc3 Nb7 17. Bc6 $36 {This looks like a disaster for Black.}) 15. Nc6 Nxc6 16.
Bxc6 {Now the rook on a8 is trapped!} Bd7 17. Bxa8 Qxa8 18. Qc4 $16 {Black
definitely has some compensation thanks to the bishop pair, but White is
clearly much better as his d5-pawn is very strong.} *

