{[%evp 0,96,25,-14,38,38,38,43,48,39,39,43,36,41,41,46,34,31,35,-1,12,6,19,16,
5,11,11,-1,18,3,28,12,34,0,89,-16,46,-54,6,-62,9,-14,-4,-115,-25,-63,-62,-67,
-28,-66,-68,-70,-98,-105,-105,-129,-139,-121,-121,-132,-129,-153,-154,-136,
-148,-154,-124,-154,-154,-157,-127,-154,-224,-193,-112,-202,-227,-227,-243,
-236,-226,-241,-332,-219,-246,-254,-227,-227,-250,-227,-256,-255,-270,-387,
-415,-415,-415,-1360,-1307]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4
Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Rb1 $5 O-O 10. d5 Bxc3+ {A few next
moves are pretty much forced.} 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 {We arrived at this
position by force, now Black has a choice.} Na5 {This was played in one game
only by a 1600 player, who, however, went on to beat a 2200!} (12... Nd4 {
As retreating to the edge is very dangerous, both Aryan and Bernadskiy who had
this position in their games chose to return the pawn immediately, but now
White is simply better.} 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Qxd4 $14 {This is clearly more
comfortable for White who now can just castle and enjoy his extra central pawn.
Even the brutal e4-e5 followed by d5-d6 would be extremely strong as the
d6-pawn would tie up all of Black's pieces.} e6 (14... Qa5+ 15. Qd2 Qxd2+ 16.
Kxd2 Rd8 17. Ke3 a6 18. Bc4 b5 19. Bb3 Bd7 20. Rhc1 Kf8 21. Rc7 (21. Kd4 $1 {
It would be very natural to make this position even better by activating the
king, for example} a5 22. a3 Rdc8 23. h4 $5 $16 {White takes up even more
space and is clearly a lot better.}) 21... a5 22. a3 Ke8 23. Rbc1 Rdb8 {
White was still a little better here, but eventually Black managed to hold
after some tedious defense.} 24. e5 Ra6 25. f4 Kd8 26. R7c5 a4 27. Ba2 b4 28.
Bc4 Rab6 29. axb4 Rxb4 30. e6 fxe6 31. dxe6 Rc8 32. Bd5 Rxc5 33. Rxc5 Rb5 34.
Kd4 {1/2 (34) Mamedyarov,S (2770)-Aryan,C (2562) Caleta 2020}) 15. d6 e5 16.
Qd2 Be6 17. O-O Qf6 18. Ba4 Rfd8 19. Rxb7 (19. d7 $1 $146 {And Black would
have no way of ever untangling, this is just terrible.}) 19... Bc8 20. Re7 Rxd6
21. Re8+ Kg7 22. Qc3 Bb7 23. Rxe5 Bxe4 24. Rc5 {1/2 (24) Aleksandrov, A (2580)
-Bernadskiy,V (2586) Suwalki 2018}) 13. h4 f6 14. Rc1 $5 $146 {Instead of
continuing with the obvious h4-h5, first we provoke ...b7-b6. How can this
prove useful? Let's see!} (14. h5 g5 15. h6 Rf7 16. Nxg5 fxg5 17. Rh5 Qb6 18.
Rxg5+ Kh8 19. Bd3 Qf6 20. Rf5 Bxf5 {0-1 (20) Skrondal,I (2190)-Fluegel,S (1600)
Oslo 2009}) 14... b6 15. h5 $1 g5 (15... gxh5 16. Rxh5 {Is just a disaster for
Black. We can continue with e4-e5, possibly Ke2, Rc1-h1, etc, with an
extremely potent initiative.}) 16. Nxg5 {If Black doesn't take, we are
obviously much better, so taking is the only principled reply.} fxg5 17. Qxg5+
Kh8 (17... Kf7 $4 18. h6 $1 {Now Qg7 is about to checkmate Black, while after}
Rg8 19. Qf4+ $1 Kg6 20. Rc3 $18 {Black still ends up checkmated - just a few
moves later.}) 18. h6 Rf7 $8 19. Rc3 $1 {Finally we are making use of our
rook! Black has two possibilities here - Bf5 and Qf8, but both lead to
horrible positions.} Qf8 (19... Bf5 20. Rf3 $1 {Black's bishop, obviously,
cannot retreat because of Rxf7 and Qg7 mate, but otherwise he loses his extra
piece, ending up in a lost middlegame/endgame.} Qf8 21. Rxf5 Rxf5 22. Qxf5 Qxf5
23. exf5 $18) 20. Qe5+ Rf6 (20... Kg8 $4 21. Rg3+ $18) 21. Rf3 {The threat is
d5-d6!} Bg4 $8 22. d6 $1 Bxf3 23. dxe7 Qf7 24. gxf3 {At the moment White is
down a rook, but ideas like e8Q or Rh5-f5 are simply unstoppable.} Qe6 25. Rh5
$1 a6 26. Bd7 $5 Qxe5 27. Rxe5 Rxh6 28. e8=Q+ Rxe8 29. Rxe8+ Kg7 {In this
interesting endgame White is nearly winning as the bishop is a lot superior to
the knight and White is simply pushing his pawns with Ke2, f3-f4-f5, e4-e5-e6
etc.} 30. f4 $5 $16 {I would rather put a +- sign, but I don't want you to
feel over-relaxed, so please pull yourself together and convert that advantage
achieved after so many brilliant moves!} *

