{[%evp 0,96,25,-14,38,38,38,43,48,39,39,43,36,41,41,46,34,31,35,-1,12,6,19,16,
5,11,11,-1,18,3,28,12,34,0,89,-16,46,-54,6,-62,9,-14,-4,-115,-25,-63,-62,-67,
-28,-66,-68,-70,-98,-105,-105,-129,-139,-121,-121,-132,-129,-153,-154,-136,
-148,-154,-124,-154,-154,-157,-127,-154,-224,-193,-112,-202,-227,-227,-243,
-236,-226,-241,-332,-219,-246,-254,-227,-227,-250,-227,-256,-255,-270,-387,
-415,-415,-415,-1360,-1307]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4
Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Rb1 $5 O-O 10. d5 Ne5 11. O-O {
Please note that at the moment of writing this position was reached in 7 games
only, so it's very difficult to determine what Black's most reliable defense
actually is.} (11. Nxe5 $5 {This is likely to suddenly transpose to one of the
variations in 8.Rb1 O-O! However, while apparently we didn't go 8.Bb5 to
tranpose to 8.Rb1, we have avoided, arguably, the most critical line 8.Rb1 O-O
9.Be2 cxd4 10.cxd4 Qa5+. The line we are getting is considered decent from the
theoretical perspective, but, unless Black actually did his homework in this
very variation, he isn't going to have an easy life. Please, pay detailed
attention to the analysis of the game between Yu and Nepo below, as this
attempt seems to be rather critical if White is to hope for any advantage. I
believe that my recommendation in the main line is very promising for White as
well, but the idea that Yu went for leads to a completely different kind of
positions so you might want to investigate this carefully, too!} Bxe5 12. O-O
$5 {A very principled idea: not only is White offering a pawn sacrifice but
also he is pretty much forcing Black to take, or otherwise White will easily
build a powerful center, reaching a clearly beneficial position.} (12. Qd2 e6
13. f4 Bc7 14. Bc4 {This is the aforementioned 8.Rb1 transposition. Here, I
believe, White gets an advantage in all the lines but one:} a6 $1 15. a4 b5 $1
{Again, I wouldn't think people who don't know this line would be willing to
sacrifice a pawn! At least, not necessarily.} 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bxb5 exd5 18.
Bc6 Ra6 19. Bxd5 Rd6 {Thanks to the pin over the d-file Black gets his pawn
back.} 20. O-O Bf5 21. exf5 Rxd5 22. Qc2 Rxf5 $11) 12... a6 {Instead of taking
immediately, Nepo prefers to insert ...a7-a6 first, hoping to later play ...
b7-b5, grabbing space on the queenside.} (12... Bxc3 $5 $146 {This
continuation has never been tried, but I feel it makes sense to capture
immediately, as it is clear that Black has to take the pawn. At the same time,
it's not obvious at all if Black is going to need ...a7-a6, so it is not
unreasonable to delay that move for a while.} 13. Be3 b6 {Let us see what kind
of a compensation White is going for if Black simply protects everything on
the queenside.} 14. Bc6 Rb8 15. Bf4 $1 {This is it! Suddenly it transpires the
rook on b8 is trapped!} Ba6 $1 (15... e5 $5 {Now White can choose between Bh6,
grabbing the f8-rook, or dxe6, winning the exchange in a different way. In
either case, Black will have a decent compensation but the burden of proof is
definitely on him.} 16. dxe6 (16. Bh6 Bd4 17. Bxf8 $13) 16... Bxe6 17. Bxb8
Qxb8 18. Bd5 $13 {This is definitely an interesting position to play out!}) 16.
Qb3 $5 {Instead of taking an exchange, we are offering one!} (16. Bxb8 $6 Qxb8
$44 {I feel that in this version the sacrifice is not worth accepting as the
Black bishop is going to be rather active on a6 whilst ours is stuck on c6.})
16... Bd4 $1 (16... Bxf1 $2 17. Qxc3 Ba6 18. Bh6 f6 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 20. e5 $1 {
I suggest we can the analysis short here, after this forced sequence. White's
ideas include Qf3, Re1, maybe d5-d6 at some point. The Black pieces are stuck
on the last ranks, unable to display even a tiny bity of activity. White's
space advantage does not hurt his chances either, I would dare to claim White
is just clearly better here.}) 17. Rfd1 $13 {Now we not only threaten to take
on b8 at some point, but also we can continue Qa4, hitting the a6-bishop, the
a7-pawn and creating a threat of Rxd4 in many variations. This position
remains very unbalanced and complicated with both sides having an immense
number of possibilities, but I feel White is definitely enjoying being on top
of the game as he had several interesting deviations earlier, while Black had
to find many precise moves to get here. At this point, Black still has to be
quite precise as his extra pawn does not matter too much at the moment, while
White's space advantage and his active pieces obviously provide us with a lot
of dangerous possibilities. Please, also keep in mind that Black needs to be
constantly worrying about the fact that we can always accept the exchange
sacrifice, and even if some players will manage to get here, they might well
evaluate this position as a bad one for Black, reaching a conclusion that they
must have gone wrong earlier as now they are losing material. This is another
important physhological advantage that we have. But, if the positions arising
in these variations seem too crazy to you, you always have a choice: feel free
to either play 9.d5, or go for the line which I consider to be the main one in
this file.}) 13. Be2 Bxc3 (13... b5 {As I claimed earlier, refusing to take
the pawn isn't the best solution for the second player as now White easily
gets an advantage in several ways.} 14. c4 $14 {This beautiful center ensures
White of a very comfortable game, he is clearly better.} (14. a4 $5 {Also
looks nice, for example} Bxc3 15. axb5 axb5 16. Bxb5 $14 {and White is clearly
better thanks to the superior pawn structure. The c5-pawn will yet cause Black
several concerns.})) 14. Be3 Qa5 (14... b5 {Is another possibility, when after}
15. Bxc5 {White reaches a better position, especially if Black does not do
anything right now, as his central pawn and space advantage clearly account
for something. So, the only challenging move Black has now is} Qc7 $1 16. Bd4
$1 (16. Be3 $6 Bd7 $13 {Black will continue with ...b5-b4, ...a6-a5, etc.,
reaching interesting counterplay on the queenside. This is something we should
rather avoid!}) 16... Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Bd7 18. Rbc1 $36 {As we see based on this
variation, White's key idea is to trade the bishops as now Black's counterplay
is nearly non-existent while we have play on the kingside, justified by our
space advantage in the center. For example, h2-h4-h5 would be an extremely
reasonable plan here, which Black might have a rather hard time stopping.}) 15.
h4 $1 {In for a penny, in for a pound! Yu abandons his queenside, going all-in
on the other flank.} Rb8 (15... Qxa2 $6 {Is too dangerous on account of the
simple} 16. Bxc5 Re8 17. Rb6 $44 {White not only enjoys more space in the
center and initiative on the kingside, but also he keeps Black's queenside
under some severe pressure as the c8-bishop cannot get out. In this case, our
compensation is simply terrific!}) 16. h5 Bd7 17. f4 $6 {This is an
interesting plan, but I feel that White is already burning too many bridges,
which was not something necessarily worth doing.} (17. Qc1 $1 $146 {Is my
suggested improvement. Now, of course, black cannot take on a2 and e2 as Qxc3
and Bh6 will crush his position, while after} b5 $1 18. Bxc5 Rfe8 19. Qe3 $13 {
we reach a very complicated position where one of White's powerful attacking
plans could be Rb1-b3-g3!, combined with the queen transfer to the kingside -
say, to f4, g5 or h6. Obviously, this looks like a rather hard day in the
office for Black whose queen is stuck on the queenside.}) 17... Qxa2 18. hxg6
hxg6 19. Bg4 f5 20. Bh3 Qa4 21. Qxa4 Bxa4 22. Bxc5 Rf7 23. Rb6 Kh7 24. Rf3 Ba5
25. Re6 fxe4 26. Rg3 Rg8 27. f5 g5 28. Bxe7 Bc7 29. d6 Bb6+ 30. Kh2 Bd7 31. Rg6
e3 32. R3xg5 Rgg7 33. Rxg7+ Rxg7 34. Rh5+ Kg8 35. f6 Bg4 36. Rh8+ Kxh8 37.
fxg7+ Kxg7 38. Bxg4 Bc5 39. Kg3 a5 40. Kf3 a4 41. Bd7 a3 42. Be6 b6 43. Bb3 {
1-0 (43) Yu,Y (2763)-Nepomniachtchi,I (2776) Khanty-Mansiysk 2019}) 11... Nxf3+
(11... a6 $5 {This is the most popular move, but I cannot say I am fond of
Black's position.} 12. Be2 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 {If White will get to play c3-c4,
his advantage will become obvious, so Black has to take the c3-pawn.} Bxc3 14.
Be3 Qa5 (14... c4 $146 15. Qc2 {White will regain the c4-pawn and again I like
his chances a lot thanks to the extra pawn in the center.}) 15. Qb3 Bd4 16. Qb6
$5 $146 (16. Bxd4 cxd4 {Now Qb6 would lead to some roughly equal endgame, but
White lost the track and eventually lost. 0-1 (50) Alshameary Puente,I (2444)
-Martinez Ramirez,E (2217) Linares 2019}) 16... Qxb6 17. Rxb6 {White's b6-rook
is placed extremely conveniently, stopping the c8-bishop from getting in the
game. Black is a pawn up at the moment, but his pieces aren't exactly his
pride and joy, while White can make a few more improving moves like Rc1,
followed by Bxd4 and Rc7, Kf1-e2-d3 etc. In my opinion, White keeps a very
pleasant position.}) 12. Qxf3 f5 {This is definitely the most ambitious
continuation.} 13. Bc4 $5 {I, actually, like this continuation best. It was
tried in one game between two 2200-level players only, which is great as many
people wouldn't pay attention to this game. This was a correspondence game, by
the way, so this move is a novelty by over-the-board standards! Its objective
merit is also rather high as White, after a forced line, gets a position with
very little risk and great chances to keep posing problems for many more moves.
} ({As this is arguably the most critical position in 9.Rb1, we can consider a
few candidate moves for White.} 13. e5 $5 {This was the move tried by Dubov
himself, but I am not sure how much I like this continuation as the game
becomes rather double-edged and it is going to be very easy to lose control
with White, too.} Bxe5 14. Re1 Qd6 15. Bh6 a6 16. Bf1 {Here Black didn't
manage to find the best defense, which is understandable given how complicated
and murky the position is.} b5 $2 (16... Bxh2+ $1 17. Kh1 Be5 18. Bxf8 Kxf8 $44
{Would have lead to a very complicated position where I actually like Black,
at least from the practical perspective, as his dark-squared bishop is pretty
much the key piece on the board.}) 17. h4 $2 (17. a4 $1 {Would have questioned
Black's last move, as now his queenside is falling apart.} bxa4 18. Bc4 {
Now the e5-bishop is hanging, Qe3 is also a threat. Black is already on the
verge of losing.}) 17... Bd7 18. h5 c4 $36 {Black was already better and
eventually he went on to win. 0-1 (48) Dubov,D (2660) -Howell,D (2644) Doha
2016}) 13... fxe4 14. Qxe4 {Now d5-d6 would crush Black's position.
Unfortunately, he's got counterplay of his own, too!} Bf5 15. d6+ Kh8 16. Qe3 {
Everything is absolutely forced.} Bxb1 17. dxe7 Qc7 18. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 19. Re1
$13 {The forced play has finally ended. I think White has some chances to push
a bit if he installs his bishop on d5 and the pawn on c4 without blundering ...
Bd4 with disaster on the f2-square, as Black's king would be weaker in the
long run, and ideas like h2-h4-h5 could prove rather annoying.} b6 20. Qd2 Bf5
21. h3 Bf6 22. Bd5 Qg7 23. Re3 Bc8 24. Rf3 Be5 25. Re3 {Here White took a draw,
which in my opinion was clearly premature as after 25...Bf6 26.c4! he would
risk very little while enjoying a solid stable advantage. I would like to
praise the White player for amazing preparation, but you cannot win the game
if you don't play a better position! 1/2 (25) Matozo,P (2210)-Colombo Berra,F 
(2274) ICCF email 2018} *

