{[%evp 0,29,26,22,31,-9,37,37,62,51,51,51,51,51,51,51,29,13,48,42,76,83,73,77,
71,72,82,59,72,78,82,82]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3
6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 c5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Be2 Bg4 10. Rb1 O-O 11. O-O Bxf3 12. Bxf3
cxd4 13. cxd4 Bxd4 14. Rxb7 Nc6 15. Qa4 {We have seen everything until here in
the theoretical section. While I believe that most players will always pick
White in this position and would really enjoy having White here, I think it is
very important and instructive to see how White can actually benefit most from
his advantages. I believe that this game is very illustrative and instructive
in this regard.} Qd6 {As we know, Nepo chooses Qc8 instead, but the character
of the position remains the same anyway.} 16. Rb5 $1 {The rook would prove
quite irritating on d5. Also, White sets a small trap} Rfd8 (16... e6 $4 {
Would blunder the idea that White just created.} 17. Ba3 $1 $18 {White just
took c5 under control with his rook and wins an exchange.}) 17. Rd5 Qe6 18. Rd1
Bb6 {A sad necessity, as it was impossible to maintain the bishop on the long
diagonal.} (18... Bg7 {Is not possible because of} 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 (19... Nxd8
20. Qe8+ $18) 20. Rxd8+ Nxd8 21. Qe8+ Bf8 22. Bh6 $18) (18... Bf6 {Trying to
keep the bishop on this diagonal does Black no good because of several
concrete reasons. White can even choose how exactly he wishes to win} 19. Rxd8+
Rxd8 20. Rxd8+ Nxd8 21. Qe8+ Kg7 22. Qxd8 $18 {Is the simplest}) 19. Bb2 {
Now Black always need to worry about such ideas, as Qa3-Qc3, for instance.}
Rab8 {Threatening Bxf2!, so White takes measures.} 20. Bc3 (20. Qa3 {Was
possible too, but White chooses another plan - his queen is also well-placed
on a4.}) 20... Rdc8 {Black starts wasting time. However, his defensive task
was by no means easy. Now there is a new sudden problem for Black - the queen
on e6 is short on squares!} (20... Rf8 21. h3 h5 {Possibly intending something
like Rbd8, or f7-f6 followed by Ne5, would have been a better defense for
Black. Usually, it is very difficult to suggest a good piece of advice in such
positions - the better choice is not to get in them!}) 21. h3 $1 {Bg4 is a
large threat now.} h5 22. Be2 {Missing the momentum. Fortunately for White,
his position is still very good.} (22. Bxh5 $3 {Was already possible, as after}
gxh5 23. Rxh5 f6 24. e5 $1 $18 {White also drives his queen on the kingside
and soon breaks through, Black has absolutely no defense.}) 22... Kh7 (22...
Rc7 $1 {Was necessary as Black queen is about to be trapped, just as it
happened in the game. This move would prepare Qc8, keeping the fight in a very
bad position. The text loses instantly.}) 23. Bc4 $1 {Surprisingly, Black has
no defense to Rxh5 followed by Bxe6!} Nb4 24. Rxh5+ gxh5 25. Bxe6 Rxc3 26. Bxf7
$18 {And soon White went on to win. In my opinion, a really impressive game,
where Black had no fun at all since very first moves!} Rc2 27. Rf1 Rf8 28. Qb3
Kg7 29. Bxh5 Rfxf2 30. Rxf2 Rxf2 31. Qg3+ Kh8 32. Kh2 Nc2 33. Qe5+ Kg8 34. Qg5+
Kh8 35. Qh6+ Kg8 36. Qg6+ Kh8 37. Qe8+ Kg7 38. Qxe7+ Kh6 39. Qe8 Kg7 40. Kg3
Ne1 41. Qg6+ Kf8 42. Bf3 Rf1 43. Qf6+ Kg8 44. e5 Nxf3 45. gxf3 {1-0 (45)
Yakovich,Y (2576)-Danielian,E (2502) Kavala 2009} *

