{[%evp 0,85,26,24,28,6,40,38,61,51,54,46,54,54,54,58,59,48,46,35,51,51,51,62,
61,56,95,101,90,83,82,93,80,76,68,62,64,59,49,43,81,53,55,59,51,27,26,31,45,31,
18,9,28,28,53,48,36,41,36,29,32,25,33,26,26,26,25,-65,10,-52,103,103,92,92,112,
30,60,85,129,117,194,196,222,230,249,238,289,306]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O {We would arrive at the
position of our interest with a slightly different move order. While we
believe this line is inferior from the theoretical perspective, it is
important to understand how to best exploit the typical advantage that White
gets in this type of position.} 8. Nf3 c5 9. Be2 Bg4 10. O-O cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6
12. d5 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Bxa1 14. Qxa1 Na5 15. Bh6 f6 16. Bxf8 Kxf8 $16 {This is
another typical unpleasant position. The pawn on f6 weakens Black's kingside
considerably. If Black keeps his pieces around the king, White would be often
able to switch to either playing on the c-file or to creating a passer in the
center.} 17. Bg4 Nc4 18. Be6 b5 19. Re1 Qb8 20. g3 a6 21. Kg2 {A few last
moves may have not been precise, now both sides maneuver for a while.} Qe5 22.
Qc1 Kg7 23. Qc2 Qd4 24. Rd1 Qe5 25. Re1 Qd4 26. Qe2 Ra7 27. Rd1 Qc3 28. Rd3 Qa1
29. Rd1 Qc3 30. Rd3 Qa1 31. f4 Rc7 32. Kh3 Qc1 $2 {Black doesn't withstand the
pressure of the maneuvring battle and makes a mistake, now White gets
something significant in the center. Overall, even though the engine was
showing equality along the way, I feel that it is much easier to play with
White has more space and active ideas, while Black is only defending.} 33. e5
$1 Nxe5 $1 (33... fxe5 34. fxe5 $18 {Would be followed by d6 with a quick
victory}) 34. Rd1 (34. fxe5 $2 Rc2 $1 {was Black's point} 35. exf6+ exf6 36.
Qf3 Qh6+ {And Black checkmates White all of a sudden}) 34... Qc4 35. Qe1 {
Now Black's pieces are stuck, unfortunately, he cannot go} Nf3 (35... Nd7 $2 {
Because of} 36. d6 $1 {With a double attack on the queen and a rook}) 36. Qe3
Qc3 37. Rd3 Ng1+ 38. Kg2 Qb2+ 39. Rd2 Qc1 40. Bg4 Kf8 41. Bd1 {And White
finally defended everything and got ready to pick the knight, in a few moves
the game was over. It's really difficult, but also very interesting and
instructive to analyze such games where both players are showing extremely
deep ideas, but this is definitely a thing worth doing if you want to become a
better player, as the ideas learned in such analysis become lifelong friends
of yours!} Rc5 42. Qf2 Qc4 43. Rd4 {1-0 (43) Yilmaz,M (2619)-Perelshteyn,E 
(2513) Reykjavik 2018} 1-0

