{[%evp 0,85,26,24,28,6,40,38,61,51,54,46,54,54,54,58,59,48,46,35,51,51,51,62,
61,56,95,101,90,83,82,93,80,76,68,62,64,59,49,43,81,53,55,59,51,27,26,31,45,31,
18,9,28,28,53,48,36,41,36,29,32,25,33,26,26,26,25,-65,10,-52,103,103,92,92,112,
30,60,85,129,117,194,196,222,230,249,238,289,306]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5
4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4 Nxc3 6. bxc3 Bg7 7. Be3 O-O {We would arrive at the
position of our interest with a slightly different move order. While we
believe this line is inferior from the theoretical perspective, it is
important to understand how to best exploit the typical advantage that White
gets in this type of positions.} 8. Nf3 c5 9. Be2 Bg4 10. O-O cxd4 11. cxd4 Nc6
12. d5 Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Bxe5 {White got a typical advantage that we
had mentioned in the theoretical part - he has chances to get active play on
the queenside, namely over the c-file, or possibly put pressure on Black's
queenside pawns. At the same time, he can also consider the plan with f2-f4
followed by either e4-e5 or f4-f5, grabbing more space and possibly preparing
an attack.} 15. Rac1 Qa5 16. g3 {I am not so sure about this move, it was
possible to already start doubling over the c-file by means of Rc4, for
example. However, the advantage is static and would not disappear, so White
takes his time.} Rfc8 17. Rc4 Rxc4 18. Qxc4 b5 19. Qc6 Rd8 20. Rc1 Qxa2 21.
Qxb5 {Some transformation has happened in the position, as the queenside pawns
got traded. Importantly, the remaining a7-pawn is not a strength, it would not
run all the way to a1 fast. White's pieces are more active, he can try to
either win the a-pawn or create pressure himself in the center.} a5 22. Qc5 Re8
23. Bg5 Bb2 24. Rc2 Qa1+ 25. Kg2 $16 {White managed to obtain exactly what he
needed - he has strong pressure on the e7-pawn now and the Black pieces are
stuck on a completely different part of the board.} Bf6 26. Bh6 {White prefers
to keep the tension, but I think taking was also very interesting.} (26. Bxf6
$5 {Was a good technical decision} Qxf6 (26... exf6 {Gives White a passer on
the d-file , which is pretty horrible for Black, too.}) 27. Qxa5 $16 {And
White will torture Black for a hundred moves here, the position is very
difficult for him. Even the rook endgame 5 vs 4 is almost lost, as opposed to
a theoretical draw in 4 vs 3.}) 26... Bg7 27. Bd2 Qb1 (27... a4 28. Qc4 {
Intending Ra2, White would also win a pawn in a few moves, as Ra8 doesn't work}
Ra8 $4 29. Qc8+ $1 Rxc8 30. Rxc8+ Bf8 31. Bh6 {And the weakness of the last
rank tells, White wins.}) 28. Bxa5 $16 {Eventually White won the pawn and
after some long fight the game as well.} Ra8 29. Bd2 h5 30. Qc4 h4 31. Bg5 hxg3
32. hxg3 Be5 33. Rc1 Qb7 34. Qc6 Rb8 35. Qxb7 Rxb7 36. f4 Bg7 37. Rc8+ Kh7 38.
Kf3 f6 39. Bh4 Rb3+ 40. Ke2 Kh6 41. Rc7 g5 42. Rxe7 gxh4 43. gxh4 Rb6 44. Kf3
Bf8 45. Rf7 Bc5 46. Kg4 Bf2 47. Rf8 Be1 48. Rc8 Rb4 49. Kf5 Kg7 50. h5 Bh4 51.
Rc7+ Kh6 52. Rc6 Rd4 53. Re6 Kg7 54. d6 Kh7 55. e5 fxe5 56. fxe5 Be1 57. Rg6
Bc3 58. Rg3 Bb2 59. Re3 Kg7 60. Re4 Rd1 61. Ke6 Bc1 62. d7 Kh6 63. Re1 Rxe1 64.
d8=Q Kxh5 65. Qf6 {1-0 (65) Magallanes, F (2337)-Marcos Nozar,J (2307) ICCF
email 2008} 1-0

